BLUETONGUE - EUROPE (27): BTV-8, UK, VACCINATION, EU UPDATE
***********************************************************
A ProMED-mail post
<http://www.promedmail.org>
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
<http://www.isid.org>

Date: Fri 23 May 2008
Source: Defra information bulletin Ref: 154/08 [edited]
<http://www.defra.gov.uk/news/2008/080523a.htm>


Bluetongue update: extension of the protection zone to allow further
vaccination, and future plans
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Defra has today [23 May 2008] announced that the Bluetongue
Protection Zone will be extended again on Mon 26 May 2008, following
the delivery of additional doses of Bluetongue vaccine.

Vaccination is only permitted within the Protection Zone; therefore,
in accordance with the Bluetongue vaccination plan, the Protection
Zone will be extended to cover all of Devon (including the Unitary
Authorities of Plymouth and Torbay). The Surveillance Zone is unaffected.

Defra has also today confirmed that on current plans, which are
subject to the overall disease situation, the Protection Zone will be
further extended in the week beginning 2 Jun 2008, in line with the
expected delivery of vaccine

The intention is for Cornwall, East Riding of Yorkshire, West
Yorkshire, South Yorkshire, the District of Selby, Warwickshire and
Gloucestershire (including the Unitary Authority of South
Gloucestershire) to be brought into the Protection Zone. The Welsh
Assembly Government will also declare the current Restricted Zone in
Wales a Protection Zone.

This provides advance warning of the specific areas the Protection
Zone will extend into, and allows farmers to plan ahead and order
vaccine so that they can protect their stock at the earliest
opportunity. This is in line with the vaccination roll-out plan
published in April 2008, which outlines the criteria and
considerations under which these changes are made.

Livestock keepers in the areas coming into the Protection Zone will
be able to obtain the vaccine from the time they become part of the
Zone; however they are encouraged to order vaccine in advance through
their vet. The vaccine is available in 20ml and 50ml bottles.

Protection Zone restrictions will apply to those keepers coming into
the extended zone. Animals can only be moved out of the Protection
Zone if they are vaccinated, naturally immune or moving for
slaughter, subject to meeting certain conditions. Please refer to the
Defra website for further guidance.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail Rapporteur Mary Marshall

[For a map showing the boundaries of the Protection zone, the
Surveillance zone and the Welsh Restricted zone, as updated for 26
May 2008, go to
<http://www.defra.gov.uk/animalh/diseases/notifiable/bluetongue/pdf/declaration-bt-pzsz080523.pdf>.


EU update:

Since the start of the extraordinary BTV-8 epizootic in Europe in
2006, several BT-related projects and websites have been established
and operated. It remains, though, a tough undertaking to try obtain
an updated, comprehensive picture of the epidemiological situation
covering all affected countries. Some of the websites are the following:

<http://medreonet.cirad.fr/partners>
<http://oiebtnet.izs.it/oiebtlabnet/#>
<http://ec.europa.eu/food/animal/diseases/controlmeasures/bluetongue_en.htm>
<http://www.efsa.europa.eu/EFSA/KeyTopics/efsa_locale-1178620753812_Bluetongue.htm>
<http://www.reoviridae.org/dsRNA_virus_proteins/ReoID/BTV-mol-epidem.htm>
<http://www.reoviridae.org/dsrna_virus_proteins//outbreaks.htm>
<http://ec.europa.eu/food/animal/diseases/adns/index_en.htm> (go to
weekly summary).

One can also utilise OIE's WAHID interface at
<http://www.oie.int/wahid-prod/public.php?page=disease>, by selecting
bluetongue, the region Europe, 2007-2008. It seems that the quality
and persistency of BTV reports submitted by the countries to EU's
ADNS and to the OIE, are heterogenous.

EU member countries submit periodically their presentations on their
respective BTV situation during the monthly meetings of EU's Standing
Committee on the Food Chain and Animal Health (SCFCAH), Section :
ANIMAL HEALTH & ANIMAL WELFARE. The presentations include
epidemiological data and descriptions of control and prevention
measures. To view these individual countries' presentations, go to
<http://ec.europa.eu/food/committees/regulatory/scfcah/animal_health/presentations_en.htm#78052008>.
The most recent submitted presentations, currently available from
each country, are the following:

